Stop Using HTTP Cookies for Cross-Platform Mobile Apps

5 min read
4 hours ago

--

If you look up the difference between HTTP cookies and JSON Web Tokens (JWTs), 90% of the articles you find will immediately drag you into a security boxing match: XSS vs. CSRF. You will read endless debates about whether it is worse to have a token stolen via a malicious script or a session hijacked via a forged link.
But focusing entirely on security misses the real-world operational reality.
When you are actually in the trenches building applications, the deciding factor between a cookie and a bearer token is almost never just a security checklist. It is architecture. Specifically, it is the friction that occurs when you try to force an authentication mechanism designed for a browser into a client environment that does not care about browsers.
If you are building a server that only talks to a single web origin, cookies are an elegant, hands-off solution. If you are building a cross-platform API meant to serve a website, an iOS app, and an Android app simultaneously, forcing cookies onto your mobile clients turns your frontend codebase into a fragile, over-engineered mess.
Here is a look at why this architectural friction happens, and exactly what it looks like when it breaks down in code.
The Runtime Disconnect: Browsers vs. Native Apps
To understand why the platform matters so much, we have to look at how cookies actually work under the hood.
A cookie is not just a piece of data; it is an automation contract between the server and the browser’s native C++ engine. When an Express server sends back a Set-Cookie header, the browser catches it, stores it securely in its native cookie store, and automatically appends it to every subsequent request to that domain. The JavaScript running on your frontend does not have to lift a finger.
Mobile operating systems do not work this way.
In a React Native application, you are operating outside of a traditional browser context. While the underlying native networking layers (like NSURLSession on iOS or OkHttp on Android) have a conceptual "cookie jar," their interaction with JavaScript bridges is notoriously unreliable. They don't respect SameSite flags the same way, isolation between webviews and native code can break down, and persistent storage is handled entirely differently.

