When you try to use a stateful cookie-based session backend for a React Native app, you end up having to write manual browser emulation logic inside your JavaScript code.
The Cookie Nightmare in React Native
Let’s look at a concrete example. Imagine you built an Express.js backend a couple of years ago for a single web application. It uses traditional, stateful sessions backed by MongoDB:
// Express.js Backend (Stateful Cookie Session)
const session = require('express-session');
const MongoDBStore = require('connect-mongo');const sessionConfig = {
store: MongoDBStore.create({ mongoUrl: process.env.DB_URL }),
name: 'session',
secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET,
resave: false,
saveUninitialized: false,
cookie: {
httpOnly: true,
secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
sameSite: 'Lax',
maxAge: 1000 * 60 * 60 * 24 * 2 // 2 days
}
};
app.use(session(sessionConfig));
This works perfectly for your website. But now, you decide to build a React Native mobile app that communicates with this exact same API. Because React Native won’t reliably manage that session cookie automatically, you are forced to write complex interceptor code using Axios just to fake a browser engine:
// React Native Client (The Brittle Manual Cookie Jar approach)
import axios from 'axios';const api = axios.create({
baseURL: 'https://api.yourdomain.com/',
withCredentials: true, // Tell Axios to handle credentials
});
// A global variable holding the session string in memory
let cookieJar = '';
// Interceptor 1: Manual Extraction
api.interceptors.response.use((response) => {
const setCookie = response.headers['set-cookie'];
if (setCookie) {
const rawCookie = Array.isArray(setCookie) ? setCookie.join('; ') : setCookie;
// We have to parse out our specific session identifier manually
const sessionMatch = rawCookie.match(/session=[^;]+/);
if (sessionMatch) {
cookieJar = sessionMatch[0];
}
}
return response;
});
// Interceptor 2: Manual Injection
api.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
if (cookieJar) {
// Manually injecting the cookie header because the OS layer won't do it reliably
config.headers.Cookie = cookieJar;
}
return config;
});
Look closely at what is happening here. We are maintaining a global cookieJar variable in JavaScript memory.
This introduces a massive operational flaw: unintended logouts. The second a mobile user switches to another app and the operating system background-kills the React Native JS thread to save memory, that cookieJar string is completely wiped out. The user opens the app again and finds themselves logged out, despite the session still being perfectly valid on the MongoDB database.
Fixing this requires adding even more boilerplate to dump that string into native storage and fetch it asynchronously on every single API call.
The Clean Path: Stateless Bearer Tokens
If we shift our perspective and accept that cross-platform APIs belong to the world of stateless authorization headers, the client-side code collapses into something incredibly predictable and robust.
Instead of cookies, the server issues a stateless JWT upon a successful login. The React Native app receives this token in the response body, writes it to the device’s secure hardware enclave, and explicitly passes it back using the standard Authorization header.
Here is what that clean implementation looks like using Axios and a native secure storage library:
// React Native Client (Clean Bearer Token Approach)
import axios from 'axios';
import * as SecureStore from 'expo-secure-store'; // Or react-native-keychainconst api = axios.create({
baseURL: 'https://api.yourdomain.com/',
timeout: 15000,
});
// Inject the token from native hardware storage on every request
api.interceptors.request.use(async (config) => {
try {
const token = await SecureStore.getItemAsync('user_token');
if (token) {
config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;
}
} catch (error) {
console.error("Failed to fetch secure token", error);
}
return config;
});
Because SecureStore writes directly to iOS Keychain or Android EncryptedSharedPreferences, the token persists safely across app crashes, operating system reboots, and background resource purges. No regex matching on headers, no manual cookie parsing, and no global state variables waiting to be dropped.
The Verdict: Match the Tool to the Architecture
Choosing between these two paradigms comes down to evaluating your product’s footprint.
If your project is exclusively a web application where the frontend and backend share a common domain space, stick with HttpOnly cookies. The automated protection against XSS token theft and the lack of client-side state maintenance make it an easy win.
However, if you are designing a modern system intended to scale into native mobile or desktop clients, forcing a stateful cookie model downstream will inevitably introduce technical debt. Moving to stateless JWTs inside authorization headers might require a bit more upfront design regarding token expiration and secure storage on the web, but it ensures your API remains a clean, platform-agnostic engine capable of serving any client that can send an HTTP header.
